column9: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Unique Users)
column10: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen through unpaid distribution. (Unique Users)
column11: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen through paid distribution such as an ad. (Unique Users)
column12: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's post entered a person's screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Total Count)
column13: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's posts entered a person's screen through unpaid distribution. (Total Count)
column14: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's post entered a person's screen through paid distribution such as an ad. (Total Count)
column15: Lifetime: The number of unique people who engaged in certain ways with your Page post, for example by commenting on, liking, sharing, or clicking upon particular elements of the post. (Unique Users)
column16: Lifetime: The number of people who matched the audience targeting that clicked anywhere in your post on News Feed. (Unique Users)
column17: Lifetime: The number of clicks anywhere in your post on News Feed from the user that matched the audience targeting on it. (Total Count)
column18: Lifetime: The number of people who have given negative feedback to your post. (Unique Users)
column19: Lifetime: The number of times people have given negative feedback to your post. (Total Count)
column20: Lifetime: The number of impressions of your Page post to people who have liked your Page. (Total Count)
column21: Lifetime: The number of people who saw your Page post because they've liked your Page (Unique Users)
column22: Lifetime: The number of paid impressions of your Page post to people who have liked your Page. (Total Count)
column23: Lifetime: The number of people who like your Page and who saw your Page post in an ad or sponsored story. (Unique Users)
column24: Lifetime: The number of people who have liked your Page and clicked anywhere in your posts. (Unique Users)
column25: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length without any paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column26: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length without any paid promotion. (Total Count)
column27: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length after paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column28: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length after paid promotion. (Total Count)
column29: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed for more than 3 seconds without any paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column30: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed for more than 3 seconds without any paid promotion. (Total Count)
column31: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed more than 3 seconds after paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column32: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed more than 3 seconds after paid promotion. (Total Count)
column33: Lifetime: Average time video viewed (Total Count)
column34: Lifetime: Length of a video post (Total Count)
column35: Lifetime: The number of unique people who created a story about your Page post by interacting with it. (Unique Users)
column38: Lifetime: The number of stories created about your Page post, by action type. (Total Count)
column41: Lifetime: The number of people who matched the audience targeting on the post that clicked anywhere in the post on News Feed, by type. (Unique Users)
column44: Lifetime: The number of clicks anywhere in the post on News Feed from users that matched the audience targeting on the post, by type. (Total Count)

#OpenTVRewind - Bronx Cunt Tour 

Have you been lucky enough to see NIC Kay  work ? If not, you'll thank me later. 

NIC Kay is a performance artist whose work involves sculpture, video, sound, installation, collage and printmaking. Obsessed with the act and process of moving, the change of place, position, and the clarity/ meaning gleaned from said activity, NIC’s current transdisciplinary projects explore movement as a place of reclamation of the body, history and identity. Get to know this beautiful and brilliant artist this week during our #BCT feature.

#OpenTVRewind - #2QIK

Today will be a complicated day for a lot of us whether you're headed home to a difficult family, thinking about the irony of the whitewashed history of Thanksgiving versus the atrocities at happening at Standing Rock, or maybe you've decided to be low key and separate yourself from it all as an attempt to recenter.  

No matter what's going on with you, we hope that you are surrounded by love, cultivating joy, and eating something delicious. Two Queens in a Kitchen is more than a cooking show, the kitchen is a magical and important gathering place for many blood and chosen families. 

Enjoy Episode 4 featuring Samantha Bailey of You're So Talented  and Brown Girls and visual and performance artist and holistic healer, Kiam Marcelo Junio discussing their projects and hunger for diverse content.

Head of marketing and designer, Eli Micky on the design of Open TV: 

"Since I see the world through a strategic design lens I think that problems are pleasant opportunities waiting to be discovered. Aymar Jean Christian, the creator of Open TV approached me with a specific design problem in the late fall of 2014. As I reference my notes from the brief phone call I instantly remember resonating with a particular question that he posed: "How can we build a television network that is completely open, yet sustainable?" "

Read on about Elijah's design philosophy, inspiration, and the core of Open TV in this iteration of #VIEWPOINTS. 

Read more #VIEWPOINTS here:
#Futurewomen's Felicia Holman lays out the stakes for artists after the recent election.

#OpenTVRewind presents - #2QIK

Episode 3: Writer, performer, and filmmaker, Ricardo Gamboa with podcaster, podcast producer, and co-founder of podcast collective Postloudness, James T. Green . 

In part one of this delicious episode, Ricardo & James chat about the intersection between art and activism while making melon brochettes and a spicy shrimp cocktail.

#BrownGirls writer Fatimah Asghar tells Wear Your Voice Mag why she created the series: 

“Friendships with women of color have literally saved my life … The show is loosely based off of me and my best friend, Jamila. My friendship with Jamila is one of the most important relationships that I have ever had. I really wanted to create something that highlighted that love, because I feel like friendship/sisterhood love is not talked about as much as romantic love.”

#OpenTVRewind - #2QIK 

Check out Season 1: Episode 2 queen, Darling Squire as she moves and shakes around town. 

Catch her tomorrow night when she goes on at 10 with JC Brooks & the Uptown Sound  and Krystal Metcalfe

#OpenTVRewind presents: #2QIK 

Jump into episode 2 of #2QIK featuring Cqqchifruit, a Chicago-based queer, afr@cubarican DJ, performance artist, and designer originally from Miami, FL and Darling Squire, a dancer, healer, story teller, teacher, and student.

Cqqchifruit & Darling Shear chat about the power of a home cooked meal and the flow of capitalism while making a tostones de Cqqchifruit and Caprese Lox.

#OPENTVREWIND - Two Queens in a Kitchen 

#2QIK is much more than a cooking show, read on in this RedEye piece by Heather Schröering:

" 'Historically in a lot of black and brown communities, coming together around the kitchen is a very holistic and spiritual experience,' said Eli Micky... The concept for the show made a lot of sense to [Aymar Jean Christian and McKinnon]: Film two artists from different backgrounds in a kitchen doing the things we all do in kitchens, hanging out, making snacks and having challenging conversations.

--

The most natural form of activism to McKinnon doesn’t live on the internet. It’s about gathering and celebrating black lives, something Two Queens in a Kitchen does well. 'Those true moments of healing don’t come from a tweet in my perspective,' they said. 'They come from those intimate, raw moments that can’t be edited or distilled.' "

#OpenTVRewind is a six-week feature focusing on six original webseries. Get caught up on Season One of TWO QUEENS IN A KITCHEN, a turn-to-relevance cooking show featuring Chicago’s queens and queers of color discussing family, home, politics, culture, and art while making a healthy snack.

#OpenTVRewind - #2QIK 

Check out episode one featuring Open TV's very own creator and head of development, Aymar Jean Christian, alongside head of marketing and creator of #2QIK,  Eli Micky, as they discuss the conception of Open TV and future of artistic incubation. 

Want to know more about the beating heart of Open TV? This is the perfect place to start. If you want to take a deep dive check out http://www.weareopen.tv/development/

#OpenTVRewind Presents: Two Queens in a Kitchen 

We're back at it with week 2 of Open TV Rewind! This week's feature begs the question: what revolutions have started over stovetops? Sip some tea (careful, it's hot) and settle in for this treat.

#2QIK is a turn-to-relevance cooking show featuring Chicago’s queens and queers of color discussing family, home, politics, culture, and art while making a healthy snack.

Experience Karari, a genderqueer latinx activist In search of accomplices, frenemies, and boy toys, learning how to best love others and herself. 

#OpenTVRewind is a six-week feature focusing on six Open TV original webseries.

#OPENTVREWIND - #BeenThere
Queer love is the best love, isn't it? Meet architect, organizer, kinkster, and lover E Armea on Episode 3 of Been T/Here. 

P.S. E's boo, Cassie, shown in this video, is a founder of Project Fierce Chicago a grassroots group of youth service providers & housing advocates working to address queer youth homelessness. If you're looking for a way to help out in these tough times and you missed their fundraiser Breakfast N Beds on the 13th, donating to #ProjectFierce is a great place to start.

Okayplayer delves further into #BrownGirls with an interview with director Samantha Bailey! 

"Intersectionality is a huge theme within Brown Girls. I see Brown Girls expanding the conversation by showing [the world] that we exist. Period. We are here and if you’re going to exclude us and pretty much confirm by omission that our experiences are not valid, then that’s fine because we’ll make our own. The entire series explores this beautifully complex intersectional friendship and allows them to be multi-layered humans with well thought-out backstories." -- Sam Bailey

#OPENTVREWIND - #BeenThere

Have you had the pleasure of meeting Mama Gloria? You would remember, she glows with warmth and love wherever she goes. Did you know the average life expectancy of a trans woman of color is 35? Mama is still slaying every 👏🏽 single 👏🏽day👏🏽 in her 70s. Learn more about her in episode two of Been T/here created by André Pérez Photography

Our community is full of royalty. VAM produces consistently gorgeous and meaningful work. Dig into them.

#OpenTVCommunity #OpenTVPresents

#OpenTVRewind - #BeenThere

Get hip to the Trans Oral History Project founded by Been T/Here's creator, Andre Perez.

A catalogue of trans narratives is so sorely needed to ensure that these pillars of the queer community are heard. Especially in 2016 when trans women of color are being killed at such an alarming rate. 

The Trans Oral History Project is a collaborative media initiative dedicated to collecting stories of transgender and gender non-conforming people and making them publicly available at low or no cost.

Catch Aymar Jean Christian bringing the truth and the melanin tomorrow night at Soho House Chicago on a film panel entitled "Storytelling at the Intersection of Film and Technology in the Digital Age" with Chaz Ebert  and other experts. This event runs from 6:30 - 8:00 pm and is a part of Soho House's Film Week.
Windy City Times profiles Postloudness from #2QIK star James T. Green: "This is NPR quality. We're going to be here and you're going to take us very seriously."

#BrownGirls in Jet Magazine! "We want people to see people who look like them on screen and feel less alone in the world, especially now. It’s super important to say your story is important and it’s valid. You’re human and that’s valid. I really do believe representation matters in that way," director Samantha Bailey says of Fatimah Asghar series.

#OpenTVRewind 

Week 1: Been T/Here.

Been T/Here is a webseries created by André Pérez Photography   documenting trans* people of color in Chicago on their journeys to find love, creativity and healing. Meet Crispin Torres in episode one.

Open TV Presents: Rewind is coming soon to a browser near you. #OpenTVRewind is a six week feature focusing on six unique webseries currently available on weareopen.tv.

Now, more than ever, the vision of Open TV is forefront in our minds. Our mission is to uplift and empower marginalized voices, give them a platform to tell their own stories in an effort to strengthen our community. Have a seat at the table on Monday for the first installment: www.weareopen.tv/rewind

To the #OpenTVCommunity: We stand in solidarity with you. In the coming months, we will continue to release programs that center those who continue to be marginalized and provide space in Chicago and on our platforms to express love, frustration, hope, and strategies for change.

Keep up with the #OpenTVProgram as we revisit and uplift the stories that have brought us so much joy over the past year of sharing, learning and building. www.weareopen.tv/program
